This law, Section 288, is about who can help you with your income tax issues in front of tax authorities or a court. 

Let me break it down simply: 

If you need to go to a tax authority or a court for income tax issues, you don't have to go yourself. You can send someone else to represent you. This person is called an "authorised representative." 

To be an authorised representative, the person must be either: 

- A relative or employee of yours; 
- A bank officer who works with your bank account; 
- A lawyer who can practice in an Indian court; 
- A chartered accountant; 
- Someone who has passed a certain accounting exam; 
- Someone who has a certain degree that the tax board has approved; 
- A person who used to help with income tax issues in certain areas before this law was made; 
- Or a person who used to be an income tax practitioner before this law was made.

This law allows you to choose someone you trust to help you with your income tax issues.

